The first 23 members have been elected tothe joint traded options facility of the London CommodityExchange (LCE) and the International Petroleum exchange (IPE),the exchanges said in a statement.    More firms have applied and the final tranche will beadmitted on April one and trading is planned to start in earlyJune on the new trading floor on Commodity Quay.    Traded options need a volatile and liquid futures base tosucceed and chairman of the joint formation committee JackPatterson said the existing LCE cocoa, coffee, sugar and IPEgas oil contracts should have no difficulty in providing this. Reuter&#3;